</opentopic:map><concept break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_1" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="what_is_linux" oid="what_is_linux" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">What is Linux</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc "> </shortdesc>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <p class="- topic/p ">Just like Windows and Mac, Linux is an operating system. It is created by Linux Torvalds
            who was designed the core of the operating system back when he was a student for one of
            his classes. It is based on UNIX, but it has a greater success, because of the great
            community, open-source and hey, it is free!</p>
        <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/OIP.jfif" id="unique_1_Connect_42_image_fhn_gqz_xpb" nd:nd-id="image_fhn_gqz_xpb" placement="break"/>
        <p class="- topic/p ">Open source means that you have unlimited access to the code and you can design
            everything as you want. And for that reason there are hundreds of different
            interpretations for Linux, that are called Distributions or distros. Distros may be
            represent as different flavors, from one User Interface to another, they may have
            different settings but from the inside they are still Linux. Here is List of the most
            common ones: </p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> - Ubuntu</p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> - Linux Mint </p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> - Debian</p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> - Fedora</p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> - Open Suse</p>
    </conbody>
</concept><concept break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_2" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled3" oid="untitled3" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">What is Linux Shell? </ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc "/>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <p class="- topic/p "> Shell is a program in Linux, which reads an given input from the user {command and
            parameters} and based on that input gives an output. Shell can be runed from both GUI
            and CLI. </p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">There are Linux distribution that don‚Äôt have Graphical Interfaces, so you must learn to
            navigate easily from the file system from command line first. So, go ahead, install
            Linux on your computer or run it with Virtual Machine. After the installation press
            Ctrl,Alt + T, and I will wait for you in the next chapter.</p>
        <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-31-15.png" id="unique_2_Connect_42_image_u4p_tqz_xpb" nd:nd-id="image_u4p_tqz_xpb" placement="break"/>
        <p class="- topic/p "/>
    </conbody>
</concept><concept break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_3" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled4" oid="untitled4" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
