    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">There are Linux distribution that don‚Äôt have Graphical Interfaces, so you must learn
        to navigate easily from the file system from command line first. So, go ahead, install Linux
        on your computer or run it with Virtual Machine. After the installation press Ctrl,Alt + T,
        and I will wait for you in the next chapter.</shortdesc>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <p class="- topic/p "/>
    </conbody>
</concept><task break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic task/task " id="unique_4" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled5" oid="untitled5" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">pwd</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">This command is used for knowing where you are on the file system.</shortdesc>
    <taskbody class="- topic/body task/taskbody ">
        <prereq class="- topic/section task/prereq " id="unique_4_Connect_42_prereq_l2h_4rz_xpb" nd:nd-id="prereq_l2h_4rz_xpb">
            <p class="- topic/p " id="unique_4_Connect_42_o" nd:nd-id="o">You must have installed Linux or run it with through a virutal machine</p>
            <p class="- topic/p " id="unique_4_Connect_42_i" nd:nd-id="i">You must have opened the terminal with the combination of Ctrl+Alt+T or from
                the menu ‚Üí terminal</p>
        </prereq>
        <context class="- topic/section task/context ">
            <p class="- topic/p "> The first command from this chapter is going to be one of the most important ones.
                It simply says:</p>
            <p class="- topic/p "> Print Working Directory. As we know the directory is just a file, which is
                representing a content, or dynamic linking with flag which tells us that this file
                is a directory. We can move through the system when we are going to such a file. So
                pwd will basically print the current directory which we are in at the moment.</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">
                <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-33-24.png" id="unique_4_Connect_42_image_kfn_ld1_ypb" nd:nd-id="image_kfn_ld1_ypb" placement="break"/>
            </p>
        </context>
        <steps-unordered class="- topic/ul task/steps-unordered " id="unique_4_Connect_42_steps-unordered_r2w_ch1_ypb" nd:nd-id="steps-unordered_r2w_ch1_ypb">
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open Linux Terminal</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Enter the command pwd</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type Enter</cmd>
            </step>
            
        </steps-unordered>
    </taskbody>
</task><task break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic task/task " id="unique_5" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled6" oid="untitled6" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">ls</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">Lists all items in the current directory.</shortdesc>
    <taskbody class="- topic/body task/taskbody ">
        <prereq class="- topic/section task/prereq " id="unique_5_Connect_42_prereq_mwr_mg1_ypb" nd:nd-id="prereq_mwr_mg1_ypb">
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have installed Linux or run it with through a virutal machine</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have opened the terminal with the combination of Ctrl+Alt+T or from
                the menu ‚Üí terminal</p>
        </prereq>
        <context class="- topic/section task/context "><p class="- topic/p ">ls is short for list and it does as it says. It lists every file in the current
                directory.</p><p class="- topic/p ">Q: For example I have a directory named ‚ÄúA‚Äù, and in it there are
                files called ‚Äúa1‚Äù,‚Äùb1‚Äù.</p><p class="- topic/p "> What will be the output from the terminal when I give
                the input ‚Äúls‚Äù ?</p> A: The answer is simple. It depends. Read once again the
            description for the command pwd and you will now why it depends. So if we are in
            currently in the location of A it will display a1, b1. Otherwise the answer is: what is
            having in the directory of {pwd}.<p class="- topic/p ">
                <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-34-16.png" id="unique_5_Connect_42_image_x1b_qd1_ypb" nd:nd-id="image_x1b_qd1_ypb" placement="break"/>
            </p></context>
        <steps-unordered class="- topic/ul task/steps-unordered " id="unique_5_Connect_42_steps-unordered_f1f_hh1_ypb" nd:nd-id="steps-unordered_f1f_hh1_ypb">
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open Linux Terminal</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Enter the command ls</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type Enter</cmd>
            </step>
            
        </steps-unordered>
    </taskbody>
</task><concept break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_6" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled7" oid="untitled7" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">What are Linux Permissions</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc "/>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <p class="- topic/p ">So after we have a concept about the file system and the commands pwd and ls, it is time
            to know about Linux permissions and command options, flags: </p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">
            <div class="- topic/div "> Here we are on our way to learn more about Linux.<p class="- topic/p "> So basically, Permissions is
                    what are the accessibilities from the users to the files.</p><p class="- topic/p "> There is the
                    One User which has all the rights and it is called Super User, but for that
                    later.</p><p class="- topic/p "> On our computer there can be many users that are can access the
                    file system. But how to control access for all of them? The answer is by putting
                    them in a groups and describe which groups have access. This is controlled by a
                    bit mask.</p><p class="- topic/p "> Everything in Linux is files!</p><p class="- topic/p "> Permissions: </p><p class="- topic/p "> 1 ‚Äì
                    execute</p><p class="- topic/p "> 2 ‚Äì write</p><p class="- topic/p "> 3 ‚Äì write and execute</p><p class="- topic/p "> 4 ‚Äì read</p><p class="- topic/p "> 5 ‚Äì
                    read and execute</p><p class="- topic/p "> 6 ‚Äì read and write</p><p class="- topic/p "> 7 ‚Äì read, write and execute ‚Äì
                    full accessibility. </p> The bit masking is done by this 8 numbers (0 ‚Äì has no
                access to the file). This numbers represents the words read, write, execute, and by
                bits are 0, 1, 0 ‚Äì cannot do {read, write or execute} 1 ‚Äì can do. So if we want the
                user to can read and execute the number is 5 and it is calculated by 0 and 1s read
                write execute 1 0 1 -&gt; by 10‚Äôs system is equal to 5. That is how it is
                calculated.</div>
        </p>
    </conbody>
</concept><concept break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_7" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled8" oid="untitled8" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">What are flags?</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc "/>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <p class="- topic/p "> Flags are simply options to the commands. As far we know how to list the files that are
            in the current directory. It is done by ls command. We also know a little bit about
            permissions. So let‚Äôs see how we can see the permissions on the files. It is done by
            giving the command ls a flag l ‚Äì for long</p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">ls -l</p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">Now we can see a list of files with their permissions and there are rwe (read write
            execute), </p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> but why are they repeated 3 times.</p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> It is because the permissions are grouped by: Owner of the file rights, Group Rights,
            Other Rights.</p>
    </conbody>
</concept><concept break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_8" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled9" oid="untitled9" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">Linux Manual</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc "/>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <p class="- topic/p ">That‚Äôs cool, but how to see which command, which options have ? </p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> The answer is man. The Linux embedded manual for short man is a command where you can
            find the all information for Linux in one place. Without using of internet, it is on
            your computer and it is available 24/7. And it is a command.</p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">Q:But how to use man?</p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> A1: First try to understand it by yourself. Think. If you not manage to understand the
            answer it will be provided by A2.</p>
        <p class="- topic/p "> A2: man man ‚Äì how tricky üòä </p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">
            <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-35-08.png" id="unique_8_Connect_42_image_uvk_k21_ypb" nd:nd-id="image_uvk_k21_ypb" placement="break"/>
        </p>
    </conbody>
</concept><task break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic task/task " id="unique_9" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled10" oid="untitled10" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">cd</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">Change directory command is used to move through the file system.</shortdesc>
    <taskbody class="- topic/body task/taskbody ">
        <prereq class="- topic/section task/prereq " id="unique_9_Connect_42_prereq_jph_sg1_ypb" nd:nd-id="prereq_jph_sg1_ypb">
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have installed Linux or run it with through a virutal machine</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have opened the terminal with the combination of Ctrl+Alt+T or from
                the menu ‚Üí terminal</p>
        </prereq>
        <context class="- topic/section task/context ">
            <p class="- topic/p "> The cd or change directory is used to move through the file system easily. For
                example if there you are located in the Downloads and there is directory called
                potato and you want to go there you have to enter the command cd potato</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">
                <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-36-00.png" id="unique_9_Connect_42_image_l4y_c21_ypb" nd:nd-id="image_l4y_c21_ypb" placement="break"/>
            </p>
        </context>
        <steps class="- topic/ol task/steps ">
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open Linux Terminal</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type the command cd</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type the name of the directory you want to enter as a first parameter of the
                    command</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Press Enter</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">List all of the directories to make sure you are on the right direcotory</cmd>
            </step>
        </steps>
    </taskbody>
</task><task break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic task/task " id="unique_10" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled11" oid="untitled11" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">mkdir, rmdir</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">Yhe commands mkdir and rmdir are making and deleting directories.</shortdesc>
    <taskbody class="- topic/body task/taskbody ">
        <prereq class="- topic/section task/prereq " id="unique_10_Connect_42_prereq_etd_wg1_ypb" nd:nd-id="prereq_etd_wg1_ypb">
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have installed Linux or run it with through a virutal machine</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have opened the terminal with the combination of Ctrl+Alt+T or from
                the menu ‚Üí terminal</p>
        </prereq>
        <context class="- topic/section task/context "><p class="- topic/p ">Make directory or mkdir is basically making a directory and place it on your
                current location</p>Remove direcotry or rmdir Just like mkidr only it is doing the
            opposite thing.<p class="- topic/p ">
                <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-36-46.png" id="unique_10_Connect_42_image_sgz_n21_ypb" nd:nd-id="image_sgz_n21_ypb" placement="break"/>
            </p></context>
        <steps class="- topic/ol task/steps ">
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
