    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">touch, rm</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">The commands touch and rm are creating and deleting files.</shortdesc>
    <taskbody class="- topic/body task/taskbody ">
        <prereq class="- topic/section task/prereq " id="unique_11_Connect_42_prereq_vdp_xg1_ypb" nd:nd-id="prereq_vdp_xg1_ypb">
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have installed Linux or run it with through a virutal machine</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have opened the terminal with the combination of Ctrl+Alt+T or from
                the menu ‚Üí terminal</p>
        </prereq>
        <context class="- topic/section task/context ">
            <p class="- topic/p ">touch is using for two things. The first purpose is to make file by doing</p>
            <p class="- topic/p "> touch &lt;name of the file&gt; and it place an empty file in your current location. And
                the second thing it does is to change the -last modified time of the file to the
                time when the command is executed.</p>
            <p class="- topic/p "/>
            <p class="- topic/p ">The command rm or remove is used to remove a single file from your current locations.
                Just provide the command a parameter ‚Äì the name of the file which you want to be
                removed and it is done. The most common used flags of the remove command are -r and
                -f -r -&gt; recursively it removes every file from the directory of your choice . -f -&gt;
                force, without asking for permissions on every step of the deleting process. Try rm
                -rf / üòä or Or don‚Äôt ! // It will remove our your files including the Linux OS.</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">
                <image class="- topic/image " href="file:/C:/Users/Katy/Desktop/Linux/a/Screenshot%20from%202021-06-13%2016-37-55.png" id="unique_11_Connect_42_image_yrm_z21_ypb" nd:nd-id="image_yrm_z21_ypb" placement="break"/>
            </p>
        </context>
        <steps class="- topic/ol task/steps ">
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open Linux terminal</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type the comand touch and then the name of the file you want to create or
                    update</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Press Enter</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">After you list the items in the current directory you will seethat the file is
                    either created or updated</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type the command rm, to remove the file you recently created, then type the
                    name of the file</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Press Enter</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">You will see, as you list the items in the current directory, that your file is
                    deleted.</cmd>
            </step>
        </steps>
    </taskbody>
</task><task break-before="true" is-chapter="true" class="- topic/topic task/task " id="unique_12" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="untitled13" oid="untitled13" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">Cp and Mv</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">The commands cp and mv are coping and moving files through the file
        system.</shortdesc>
    <taskbody class="- topic/body task/taskbody ">
        <prereq class="- topic/section task/prereq " id="unique_12_Connect_42_prereq_y5n_zg1_ypb" nd:nd-id="prereq_y5n_zg1_ypb">
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have installed Linux or run it with through a virutal machine</p>
            <p class="- topic/p ">You must have opened the terminal with the combination of Ctrl+Alt+T or from
                the menu ‚Üí terminal</p>
        </prereq>
        <context class="- topic/section task/context "><p class="- topic/p ">Cp for copy and mv for move are commands which are used to organize your files
                in other directories and copy their content.</p><p class="- topic/p "> the syntax is: </p><p class="- topic/p "> cp
                &lt;file to be copied&gt; &lt;where to be copied&gt;</p> Mv &lt;file to be moved&gt;
            &lt;where to be moved&gt; * the mv command can be used also to rename files.</context>
        <steps class="- topic/ol task/steps ">
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Open Linux Terminal</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Make a file, like it is described on the previous chapter</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type the command cp to copy the file</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type as a First parameter the name of the file that you are going to copy</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Type as a Second Parameter the location which you want the file to be copied
                    at.</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Press Enter</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">Go to the location which you provided on step 5.</cmd>
            </step>
            <step class="- topic/li task/step ">
                <cmd class="- topic/ph task/cmd ">After you list the elements of the current directory, you will find out that
                    there is a copy of the original file.</cmd>
            </step>
        </steps>
    </taskbody>
